issue.title: security: allow SessionLog object to be passed to session_log arg
issue.body:
TL;DR: allow SessionLog object to be passed to session_log argument for BaseConnection

Netmiko logs all channel communication to a file via its own SessionLog for each device interaction. While SessionLog filters the username and password out automatically, there may be a case where you want more words/phrases sanitized in the session log. Currently, you can only pass a string or BufferedIOBase subclass to the session_log argument, which doesn't allow you to edit the SessionLog no_log argument. The no_log argument allows you to pass in a dict with words that you want sanitized from the session log.

By adding the ability to pass in a SessionLog object, a user can customize the no_log argument, which allows for an arbitrary number of words to be sanitized in the logs, not just the username and password.

comment.body:
You are initializing the SessionLog object with `record_writes=True`. This implies you will see the "written" data and the echoed data. Consequently, you will have a duplication of many things (i.e. these are the duplicates you see in the log file).

Yeah, yes an already open() session log object would need passed in. So the expectation is your code would do the following:

```
nm_session_log = SessionLog(
    file_name=f"device_logs/testing.log",
    no_log=sanitize_secrets,
    record_writes=False,        # changed to False which is also the default
)
nm_session_log.open()
```

I am open to either way...as calling open() on an already open() SessionLog object I believe is a no-op (so it would also probably be fine if we included the `open()` call in the Netmiko code (as you proposed above).

comment.body:
@ktbyers - I cloned the repo and tried passing in a SessionLog object and found a weird bug.

Before I get into the bug, I found that self.session_log does need manually opened in order for it to be saved to a file. Below is a snippet of code I had to add in order for the session log to save to a file.

```
            elif isinstance(session_log, SessionLog):
                # SessionLog object
                self.session_log = session_log
                self.session_log.open() # <-- had to add
            else:
                raise ValueError(
                    "session_log must be a path to a file, a file handle, "
                    "SessionLog object, or a BufferedIOBase subclass."
                )
```

Once I added self.session_log.open(), I noticed that the config and the channel log was writing to the file, causing duplicate logging. Here's a snippet of the logs:

```
terminal width 511
danslab-sw01#
danslab-sw01#terminal width 511
danslab-sw01#terminal length 0
terminal length 0
danslab-sw01#

danslab-sw01#

danslab-sw01#configure terminal
configure terminal
Enter configuration commands, one per line.  End with CNTL/Z.
danslab-sw01(config)#

danslab-sw01(config)#logging host ********
logging host 10.1.1.1
danslab-sw01(config)#logging host 10.1.1.2
logging host 10.1.1.2
danslab-sw01(config)#

danslab-sw01(config)#end
end
danslab-sw01#

danslab-sw01#

danslab-sw01#exit
```

And here's the associated script I used for testing:

```
from netmiko import ConnectHandler
from netmiko.session_log import SessionLog


sanitize_secrets = {
    "log_server": "10.1.1.1",
}

nm_session_log = SessionLog(
    file_name=f"device_logs/testing.log",
    no_log=sanitize_secrets,
    record_writes=True,
)

device = {
    "device_type": "cisco_ios",
    "host": "10.1.1.1",
    "username": "cisco",
    "password": "cisco",
    "session_log": nm_session_log,
}

cfg_file = "test_config.txt"
with ConnectHandler(**device) as net_connect:
    output = net_connect.send_config_from_file(cfg_file)
```

I figure one of the Cisco subclasses of BaseConnection is writing the additional config lines in the session log, but wanted your opinion on it before I dive into the code and create another PR.

pull_request.title: Updated Adtran Driver - Fixed send_command sync and enable mode issues.
pull_request.body:
- Fixed `send_command()` sync issues by re-enabling `global_cmd_verify` via True.  My testing on the Adtran OS 1550-24p switch showed the problems were fixed once enabled.
- Fixed `enable()` mode issues that occur when AAA is configured but not syncing properly, which causes it to fail back to the local database.  When this happens, it rejects the first Secret Password attempt and prompts for a 2nd Secret Password after providing a message, which would be the locally defined enable password.

issue.title: Updated Adtran Driver - Fixed send_command sync and enable mode issues.

comment.body:
@Gatorjosh14 I made a few minor updates.

I broke out "Falling back" such that it was no longer coupled to the "enable_pattern" variable. That variable has a different use so I didn't want to overload it with a new use here.

Second, I removed the `def __init__()` method from the adtran.py file and just had it fall back to the default in `base_connection.py` for global_cmd_verify. 

This default value is None which means to use the method specific cmd_verify for send_command (True) and for send_command_timing (False). 

You can override both of these by adding the cmd_verify argument to the given method.

For example:

```
netmiko_obj.send_command_timing(command, cmd_verify=True)
```

issue.title: Netmiko cannot recognize "sshpass alias" while using ProxyCommand
issue.body:
My setup is:
[WSL on Windows 10] ----> [Jump Server] -----> [Cisco Device]

I have used an alias in `.bashrc` to allow me to login to the JumpServer without a password. This was tested and confirmed in the CLI. SSH keys are not an option and this is a lab environment. 

`alias my_sshpass='sshpass -p "myPass" ssh'`

The following is an excerpt from the `~/.ssh/config`
```
Host JumpServer
		KexAlgorithms +diffie-hellman-group-exchange-sha1
		Ciphers aes128-ctr,aes192-ctr,aes256-ctr,aes128-cbc,3des-cbc
		HostKeyAlgorithms +ssh-rsa
		

Host cisco1
		Ciphers aes128-ctr,aes192-ctr,aes256-ctr,aes128-cbc,3des-cbc
		KexAlgorithms +diffie-hellman-group1-sha1
		StrictHostKeyChecking no
		ProxyCommand my_sshpass -W %h:%p JumpServer  <<<<<<<<<<<< This Alias is not recognized in my python script
		User myUser
```

**Netmiko Error**

``FileNotFoundError: [Errno 2] No such file or directory: 'my_sshpass'`


Even when running it on the CLI `ssh cisco1`
This is the error

```
/bin/bash: line 1: exec: my_sshpass: not found
kex_exchange_identification: Connection closed by remote host
Connection closed by UNKNOWN port 65535
```

comment.body:
@waleedqq Yeah, it is likely that Netmiko doesn't use your shell at all to execute the `ProxyCommand` (and consequently, the alias is entirely unknown to Netmiko).

I probably would try to embed the command directly in Python and use an `environment variable` to read the password (which should be very similar from a security perspective as using the alias).
